`const newState = { ...state, count: 1 }`. You've seen this exact syntax in React. The three dots `...` are called the **Spread Operator**.

### Expanding Collections
The spread operator takes an object (or an array) and unpacks all of its contents into a new object (or array). 

This is crucial because, as you learned in Lesson 28, some methods mutate data. In React, **you are never allowed to mutate original state directly.** You must make a copy first.

```javascript
// Spreading Arrays
const listA = [1, 2];
const listB = [3, 4];
const combined = [...listA, ...listB]; // [1, 2, 3, 4]

// Spreading Objects
const node = { id: "abc", health: 95 };

// This creates a BRAND NEW object in memory. 
// It copies everything from 'node' into it.
const copy = { ...node }; 
```

### Overwriting Properties
The true power of spread is copying an object and updating one specific piece of it at the same time.

```javascript
const user = { name: "Alice", role: "user", status: "active" };

// Read as: "Unpack user, then overwrite role"
const upgradedUser = { ...user, role: "admin" };

console.log(upgradedUser); 
// { name: "Alice", status: "active", role: "admin" }
```
*Note: The order matters! If you put `role: "admin"` BEFORE `...user`, the old role inside `user` will overwrite your new one.*

